On Tue, 2003-07-22 at 14:02, J. B. Rainsberger wrote:
&gt; &gt;So said jxingtang on 2003-07-22 --------------------
&gt; &gt;I do not know whether this is a duplicated question. I have a program 
&gt; &gt;with large number of console output from different source. Basically, 
&gt; &gt;I am using System.out.println(...). How could I verify those outputs 
&gt; &gt;are correct? Thanks!
&gt; 
&gt; 1. Don&#39;t use System.out in your application directly. Your application
&gt; components should accept a PrintWriter as a parameter somewhere.
&gt; 2. In your tests, substitute a PrintWriter wrapping a StringWriter in
&gt; place of System.out. This is easy to verify.

I agree with both of J. B.&#39;s points above.  However, at some points in
the past I have been obligated to use class libraries that write to
System.out, and which I cannot change.  So, to test code that uses these
libraries, I&#39;ve found that I get a lot of mileage out of creating a
little &quot;ConsoleTester&quot; helper class, which appears below.  The basic
idea is, in my unit test I create a ConsoleTester, then exercise the
code I want to test, then get the output that was written to System.out
from the ConsoleTester and make assertions about it.

Again, please do not misunderstand:  I don&#39;t like this approach.  In my
own code, I do not write to System.out, and I recommend that others
avoid doing so as well.

Cheers,

bn

public class ConsoleTester {
    private static final PrintStream originalOut = System.out;
    private static final PrintStream originalErr = System.err;
    private ByteArrayOutputStream out;
    private ByteArrayOutputStream err;

    public ConsoleTester() throws IOException {
        resetStdout();
        resetStderr();
    }

    public final void resetStdout() {
        out = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
        System.setOut(new PrintStream(out));
    }

    public final void resetStderr() {
        err = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
        System.setErr(new PrintStream(err));
    }

    public String getStdout() {
        return out.toString();
    }

    public String getStderr() {
        return err.toString();
    }

    public void shutdown() {
        System.setOut(originalOut);
        System.setErr(originalErr);
    }

    protected void finalize() throws Throwable {
        shutdown();
        super.finalize();
    }
}
